description:
A Masterclass led by Professor Tom Woolley with case studies from the Co-housing Network, Co-op Housing Movement and the Energy Saving Co-op.
Low energy building solutions for new construction and renovation can be complex and technocratic. They are not always user friendly and may be imposed without the occupants of houses and buildings understanding them. Managing buildings, whether it is simply opening windows, changing filters and tweaking thermostats, is a crucial feature of saving energy. The Co-operative and Co-housing movements can offer a user focussed alternative approach to design and professionals can learn from the experience of such groups.&nbsp;

&nbsp;
